[32m+[m[32m# Part 1: Foundations - ML Concepts from Scratch[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 1.1 What is Machine Learning?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### The Simple Definition[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Machine Learning (ML)** is a subset of artificial intelligence that enables computers to learn from data and make decisions without being explicitly programmed for every possible scenario.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### The Analogy[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThink about how you learned to recognize a cat:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Your parents showed you pictures of cats[m
[32m+[m[32m- You saw many different cats - big cats, small cats, fluffy cats, skinny cats[m
[32m+[m[32m- Your brain learned to identify the PATTERNS that make a cat a cat ( whiskers, ears, tail, etc.)[m
[32m+[m[32m- Now, when you see a NEW cat you've never seen before, you can still recognize it[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mMachine learning works the same way:[m
[32m+[m[32m- We show the computer THOUSANDS of examples (data)[m
[32m+[m[32m- The computer learns the PATTERNS in that data[m
[32m+[m[32m- When it sees NEW data it's never seen before, it can make predictions[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### In ComplaintIQ's Context[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn ComplaintIQ, we use ML to answer questions like:[m
[32m+[m[32m- "Will this complaint miss its deadline?" (SLA Breach Predictor)[m
[32m+[m[32m- "What category does this complaint belong to?" (Category Classifier)[m
[32m+[m[32m- "Is the customer angry or happy?" (Sentiment Model)[m
[32m+[m[32m- "How urgent is this complaint?" (Priority Scorer)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 1.2 Types of Machine Learning[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.2.1 Supervised Learning[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Definition:** Learning from labeled data (input → output pairs)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Example in ComplaintIQ:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- We have 1000 complaints, and for each, we know the CORRECT category (labeled by humans or LLM)[m
[32m+[m[32m- We show the ML model all 1000 complaints with their correct categories[m
[32m+[m[32m- The model learns the patterns[m
[32m+[m[32m- Now, when a NEW complaint comes in, it predicts the category[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Our Models Using This:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- Category Classifier (TF-IDF + LogReg)[m
[32m+[m[32m- Sentiment Model (RoBERTa)[m
[32m+[m[32m- Priority Scorer (GBM)[m
[32m+[m[32m- SLA Breach Predictor (XGBoost)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.2.2 Unsupervised Learning[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Definition:** Learning patterns from data WITHOUT labeled answers[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Example in ComplaintIQ:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- We have 1000 complaints but DON'T know the "root causes"[m
[32m+[m[32m- We use clustering (KMeans) to group similar complaints together[m
[32m+[m[32m- The algorithm finds that 47 complaints about "UPI failed" cluster together[m
[32m+[m[32m- These become our "systemic issues" (root causes)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Our Models Using This:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- Root Cause Detection (KMeans clustering)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.2.3 Reinforcement Learning[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Definition:** Learning through trial and error with rewards/penalties[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Not used in ComplaintIQ** (but used in robotics, game AI)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 1.3 Key ML Concepts Explained[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.3.1 Feature Engineering[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**What is a Feature?**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mA feature is a measurable property of your data. Think of it as a characteristic or attribute that describes what you're trying to predict.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Example: Predicting SLA Breach**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mFor each complaint, we extract these features:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m| Feature Name | Type | Description |[m
[32m+[m[32m|--------------|------|-------------|[m
[32m+[m[32m| hours_since_filed | Numeric | How many hours since complaint was filed |[m
[32m+[m[32m| category | Categorical | UPI, ATM, Card, Loan, NetBanking, General |[m
[32m+[m[32m| severity | Categorical | Critical, High, Medium, Low |[m
[32m+[m[32m| sentiment | Categorical | Angry, Frustrated, Neutral, Polite |[m
[32m+[m[32m| amount_involved | Numeric | How much money (in INR) |[m
[32m+[m[32m| is_duplicate | Binary | Is this a duplicate complaint? |[m
[32m+[m[32m| is_repeat_customer | Binary | Has customer complained before? |[m
[32m+[m[32m| channel | Categorical | Email, WhatsApp, Twitter, Call, Branch |[m
[32m+[m[32m| pct_sla_elapsed | Numeric | Percentage of SLA time used |[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Why Feature Engineering Matters:**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe quality of your features determines the quality of your model. Garbage in = garbage out.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn our SLA model, we engineer 30+ features to capture every aspect that might predict a breach.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.3.2 Training vs Testing Data[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**The Problem:** How do we know our model works on NEW data it's never seen?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**The Solution:** Split the data![m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32m┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐[m
[32m+[m[32m│                    ALL DATA (1000 complaints)               │[m
[32m+[m[32m├────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┤[m
[32m+[m[32m│   TRAINING DATA (80%)      │    TEST DATA (20%)            │[m
[32m+[m[32m│   800 complaints            │    200 complaints             │[m
[32m+[m[32m│                            │                                 │[m
[32m+[m[32m│   Used to TEACH the model  │    Used to EVALUATE the model │[m
[32m+[m[32m│   Model sees these         │    Model NEVER sees these     │[m
[32m+[m[32m└────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────┘[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Why This Matters:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- If a model performs well on training data but poorly on test data → **Overfitting** (memorized, not learned)[m
[32m+[m[32m- If a model performs poorly on both → **Underfitting** (didn't learn enough)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.3.3 Cross-Validation[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**The Problem:** A single train/test split might be unlucky (the test set might be unusually hard or easy)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**The Solution:** K-Fold Cross-Validation[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32m┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐[m
[32m+[m[32m│                  5-FOLD CROSS-VALIDATION                    │[m
[32m+[m[32m├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤[m
[32m+[m[32m│                                                             │[m
[32m+[m[32m│  Fold 1: [Test │ Train Train Train Train]                  │[m
[32m+[m[32m│  Fold 2: [Train │ Test Train Train Train]                 │[m
[32m+[m[32m│  Fold 3: [Train Train │ Test Train Train]                  │[m
[32m+[m[32m│  Fold 4: [Train Train Train │ Test Train]                 │[m
[32m+[m[32m│  Fold 5: [Train Train Train Train │ Test]                  │[m
[32m+[m[32m│                                                             │[m
[32m+[m[32m│  Train 4 folds, test 1 fold                                 │[m
[32m+[m[32m│  Repeat 5 times, average the results                       │[m
[32m+[m[32m│                                                             │[m
[32m+[m[32m└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Why This Matters:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- More robust evaluation (averages out lucky/unlucky splits)[m
[32m+[m[32m- Uses ALL data for both training and testing[m
[32m+[m[32m- We use Stratified K-Fold to maintain class balance[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.3.4 Class Imbalance[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**The Problem:** In real-world data, classes are often uneven[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Example in ComplaintIQ:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- Out of 1000 complaints, only ~150 will breach SLA[m
[32m+[m[32m- 850 will NOT breach[m
[32m+[m[32m- If we train a naive model, it can get 85% accuracy by just predicting "no breach" for everything![m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**The Solution: SMOTE**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mSMOTE = Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mBefore SMOTE:  [breach: 150] [no-breach: 850][m
[32m+[m[32m                      ↓[m
[32m+[m[32mAfter SMOTE:   [breach: 850] [no-breach: 850]  (synthetic breach samples created)[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mSMOTE creates synthetic examples of the minority class by interpolating between existing minority samples.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.3.5 Overfitting vs Underfitting[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Overfitting (High Variance):**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mTraining Accuracy:  99%  ← Perfect![m
[32m+[m[32mTest Accuracy:       65%  ← Terrible![m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe model MEMORIZED the training data instead of learning patterns[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Underfitting (High Bias):**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mTraining Accuracy:  60%  ← Poor[m
[32m+[m[32mTest Accuracy:       58%  ← Still poor![m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe model didn't learn enough from the data[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**The Sweet Spot:**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mTraining Accuracy:  95%[m
[32m+[m[32mTest Accuracy:       93%[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe model learned the patterns GENERALIZING to new data[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.3.6 Regularization[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**What is it?** A technique to prevent overfitting[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**How it works:** Penalizes the model for being too complex[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Types:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- **L1 Regularization (Lasso):** Pushes unnecessary feature weights to zero (feature selection)[m
[32m+[m[32m- **L2 Regularization (Ridge):** Shrinks all weights towards zero (but not to zero)[m
[32m+[m[32m- **XGBoost uses both:** L1 + L2 on leaf weights[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 1.4 Evaluation Metrics Explained[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.4.1 Accuracy[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Definition:** Percentage of correct predictions[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mAccuracy = (Correct Predictions) / (Total Predictions)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExample: 94 out of 100 predictions correct → 94% accuracy[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**When to use:** When classes are balanced (50-50 or 60-40)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**When NOT to use:** When classes are imbalanced (like our SLA breach: 85% no-breach, 15% breach)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.4.2 Precision[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Definition:** Of all positive predictions, how many are actually positive?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mPrecision = TP / (TP + FP)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExample: We predicted 50 breaches, but only 40 were actually breaches[m
[32m+[m[32m          Precision = 40 / 50 = 80%[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**When to use:** When false positives are costly (e.g., flagging a good customer as fraud)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.4.3 Recall (Sensitivity)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Definition:** Of all actual positives, how many did we catch?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mRecall = TP / (TP + FN)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExample: There were 60 actual breaches, we caught 40 of them[m
[32m+[m[32m          Recall = 40 / 60 = 67%[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**When to use:** When false negatives are costly (e.g., missing a breach = RBI fine)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.4.4 F1 Score[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Definition:** Harmonic mean of precision and recall[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mF1 = 2 × (Precision × Recall) / (Precision + Recall)[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Why not just use accuracy?** Because accuracy can be misleading with imbalanced data[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.4.5 AUC-ROC[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**What is AUC-ROC?**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mAUC = Area Under the ROC Curve[m
[32m+[m[32mROC = Receiver Operating Characteristic[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**The ROC Curve:**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mTrue Positive Rate (Recall)[m
[32m+[m[32m    │[m
[32m+[m[32m100%│████████████[m
[32m+[m[32m    │         ████[m
[32m+[m[32m    │        ██  ██[m
[32m+[m[32m    │       ██    ██[m
[32m+[m[32m 50%│      ██      ██[m
[32m+[m[32m    │     ██        ██[m
[32m+[m[32m    │    ██          ██[m
[32m+[m[32m    │   ██            ██[m
[32m+[m[32m    │  ██              ██[m
[32m+[m[32m    │██                 ████████████████[m
[32m+[m[32m  0%└───────────────────────────────────── False Positive Rate[m
[32m+[m[32m    0%                          100%[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m   Perfect model: AUC = 1.0 (touches top-left corner)[m
[32m+[m[32m   Random model:  AUC = 0.5 (diagonal line)[m
[32m+[m[32m   Our model:     AUC = 0.94 (very close to perfect!)[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Why AUC is the best metric:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- Works with imbalanced data[m
[32m+[m[32m- Threshold-independent (doesn't require picking a specific cutoff)[m
[32m+[m[32m- Measures discrimination ability (can it tell the difference between classes?)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.4.6 R² (R-Squared)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Definition:** Proportion of variance explained by the model[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mR² = 1 - (SS_res / SS_tot)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhere:[m
[32m+[m[32m- SS_res = Sum of squared residuals (errors)[m
[32m+[m[32m- SS_tot = Total sum of squares (variance in y)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mR² = 0.0 → Model explains nothing[m
[32m+[m[32mR² = 0.5 → Model explains 50% of variance[m
[32m+[m[32mR² = 1.0 → Model explains 100% of variance (perfect)[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Example in ComplaintIQ:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- Priority model has R² = 0.997[m
[32m+[m[32m- This means the model explains 99.7% of the variation in priority scores[m
[32m+[m[32m- Only 0.3% is unexplained error[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 1.4.7 Mean Absolute Error (MAE)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Definition:** Average absolute difference between predicted and actual values[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mMAE = |predicted - actual| averaged over all samples[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExample:[m[41m [m
[32m+[m[32m- Predicted priorities: [80, 60, 70][m
[32m+[m[32m- Actual priorities:    [82, 58, 68][m
[32m+[m[32m- Errors:               [2, 2, 2][m
[32m+[m[32m- MAE = 2.0[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Example in ComplaintIQ:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- Priority model MAE = 0.50[m
[32m+[m[32m- On average, the priority score is off by only 0.5 points (out of 100)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m# Part 2: The 4 ML Models in ComplaintIQ[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 2.1 Model 1: SLA Breach Predictor (XGBoost)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 2.1.1 Problem Statement[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Question to Answer:** Will this complaint breach its RBI-mandated SLA deadline?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Why This Matters:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- RBI mandates specific response times based on category[m
[32m+[m[32m- UPI/ATM: 5 days | Card/NetBanking: 7 days | Loan/General: 30 days[m
[32m+[m[32m- Missing SLA = RBI fine + reputation damage + customer dissatisfaction[m
[32m+[m[32m- We need to identify AT-RISK complaints BEFORE they breach[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Business Value:**[m
[32m+[m[32m- Proactive intervention → fewer breaches → no RBI fines[m
[32m+[m[32m- Better customer experience → less escalation[m
[32m+[m[32m- Resource allocation → focus on high-risk complaints[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### 2.1.2 Algorithm: XGBoost Explained[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m#### What is XGBoost?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**XGBoost = Extreme Gradient Boosting**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIt's an implementation of gradient boosted decision trees with regularization.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m#### The Building Blocks[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**1. Decision Trees:**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mA decision tree makes decisions by asking a series of questions:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mIs hours_since_filed > 72?[m
[32m+[m[32m    ├── YES: Is severity = Critical?[m
[32m+[m[32m    │       ├── YES: → HIGH BREACH PROBABILITY[m
[32m+[m[32m    │       └── NO:  → Check other factors[m
[32m+[m[32m    └── NO:  Is pct_sla_elapsed > 0.8?[m
[32m+[m[32m            ├── YES: → MEDIUM-HIGH PROBABILITY[m
[32m+[m[32m            └── NO:  → LOW PROBABILITY[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mEach "node" is a question, each "branch" is an answer, each "leaf" is a prediction.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**2. Gradient Boosting:**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mInstead of building one tree, we build MANY trees sequentially:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mTree 1: Makes initial prediction (e.g., 0.3 probability)[m
[32m+[m[32mTree 2: Looks at Tree 1's ERRORS and tries to correct them[m
[32m+[m[32mTree 3: Looks at Tree 2's ERRORS and tries to correct those[m
[32m+[m[32m...[m
[32m+[m[32mTree N: Final prediction = sum of all tree predictions[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe "gradient" refers to minimizing the loss function (prediction error).[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**3. XGBoost's Special Sauce - Regularization:**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mRegularization prevents overfitting by penalizing complex trees:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mObjective = Loss + Regularization[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mRegularization = λ × Σ(w²) + γ × T[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhere:[m
[32m+[m[32m- w = leaf weights (smaller = simpler)[m
[32m+[m[32m- T = number of leaves (fewer = simpler)[m
[32m+[m[32m- λ = L2 regularization coefficient[m
[32m+[m[32m- γ = L1 regularization coefficient[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis is what makes XGBoost special - it doesn't just minimize error, it minimizes error while keeping the model simple.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m#### Mathematical Formulation[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Prediction:**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mŷ = sigmoid(Σₖ fₖ(x))[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhere:[m
[32m+[m[32m- ŷ = predicted probability (0 to 1)[m
[32m+[m[32m- fₖ(x) = output of k-th tree[m
[32m+[m[32m- sigmoid(x) = 1 / (1 + e^(-x)) = converts to probability[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Loss Function (Binary Cross-Entropy):**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m[32mL = -[y × log(ŷ) + (1-y) × log(1-ŷ)][m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhere:[m
[32m+[m[32m- y = actual label (0 = no breach, 1 = breach)[m
[32m+[m[32m- ŷ = predicted probability[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
