[32m+[m[32m## 5.1 ML Fundamentals Questions[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q1: Explain what machine learning is to a non-technical person[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Imagine you're teaching a child to recognize cats. You show them many pictures of cats—big cats, small cats, fluffy cats. The child learns to identify the patterns that make a cat a cat: whiskers, ears, tail. Now when they see a NEW cat they've never seen before, they can still recognize it.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mMachine learning works the same way. We show the computer thousands of examples—in our case, complaints that we already know the answers to. The computer learns the patterns. Then when a NEW complaint comes in—one the computer has never seen—it can make predictions.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn ComplaintIQ, we have four models: one predicts if a complaint will miss its deadline, one identifies the category, one detects sentiment, and one scores urgency."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q2: What is the difference between supervised and unsupervised learning?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Supervised learning is like learning with a teacher. We have the right answers—we know the category, severity, and whether each complaint breached. We show the model all these examples, and it learns to predict.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mUnsupervised learning is like learning without a teacher. We don't know the answers—we just have data. The algorithm finds patterns on its own.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn ComplaintIQ, our 4 ML models use supervised learning—they're trained on labeled examples. But our Root Cause detection uses unsupervised learning (KMeans clustering) to find groups of similar complaints without being told what to look for."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q3: What is overfitting and how do you prevent it?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Overfitting is when a model memorizes the training data instead of learning the general patterns. It's like a student who memorizes all the answers to past exams but fails when given new questions.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThink of it this way: if I showed you 100 cat pictures and you memorized all 100 perfectly, you might not recognize a NEW cat you've never seen. That's overfitting.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWe prevent overfitting in several ways:[m
[32m+[m[32m1. **Train/test split:** We keep 20% of data hidden and test on it[m
[32m+[m[32m2. **Cross-validation:** We train and test 5 times, averaging results[m
[32m+[m[32m3. **Regularization:** XGBoost adds penalties for complex trees[m
[32m+[m[32m4. **SMOTE:** Creates synthetic examples to balance classes[m
[32m+[m[32m5. **Early stopping:** Stop training when test performance stops improving[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mOur XGBoost model has training accuracy of 95% and test accuracy of 94%—very close, which shows we're not overfitting."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q4: Explain AUC-ROC in simple terms[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "AUC-ROC is a way to measure how good a model is at distinguishing between two things—like separating 'will breach' from 'won't breach.'[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mImagine you're a detective trying to find the difference between two groups. A perfect detective would have zero overlap—everyone who will breach is clearly marked as 'high risk' and everyone who won't is marked as 'low risk.'[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe ROC curve plots this visually. The diagonal line is a random guess—50% accuracy. The closer our curve hugs the top-left corner, the better. A perfect model would touch the top-left corner.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mAUC is the area under this curve—a single number from 0 to 1. Our SLA model has AUC of 0.94. That's excellent—it means when we show the model two complaints, one that will breach and one that won't, it correctly identifies the higher-risk one 94% of the time."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 5.2 Model-Specific Questions[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q5: How does XGBoost work?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "XGBoost builds an ensemble of decision trees, one after another. Each new tree tries to correct the mistakes of the previous trees.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThink of it like a panel of experts:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Expert 1 gives their opinion[m
[32m+[m[32m- Expert 2 looks at what Expert 1 got wrong and corrects it[m
[32m+[m[32m- Expert 3 looks at what Expert 2 got wrong and corrects that[m
[32m+[m[32m- ... and so on[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mAfter 200 experts (trees), the final prediction is the sum of all their opinions. We pass this through a sigmoid function to convert it to a probability.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhat makes XGBoost special is regularization—it adds penalties for making the trees too complex. This prevents overfitting. We also tune hyperparameters like learning rate, max depth, and number of trees.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn our SLA model, each 'tree' is a series of yes/no questions: Is the complaint more than 80% through its SLA? Is severity Critical? Is the customer Angry? The answers lead to a prediction."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q6: How does TF-IDF work?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "TF-IDF stands for Term Frequency times Inverse Document Frequency. It's a way to turn text into numbers while giving importance to meaningful words.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mLet me break it down:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Term Frequency (TF): How often does a word appear in this document?[m
[32m+[m[32m- Inverse Document Frequency (IDF): How rare is this word across all documents?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mHere's an example: 'UPI' might appear in only 50 out of 1000 complaints—so it's RARE and important. 'The' appears in ALL 1000 complaints—so it's COMMON and not important.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mTF-IDF weight = TF × IDF[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mSo 'UPI' gets a high weight (rare but meaningful), while 'the' gets zero weight (too common).[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhen we combine this with Logistic Regression, we get a classifier that can identify categories based on the important words in each complaint."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q7: Why does sentiment model only have 48% agreement with LLM?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "This is actually a mapping issue, not a model failure.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mOur LLM classifier uses 4 sentiment classes: Angry, Frustrated, Neutral, and Polite.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe RoBERTa model uses 3 sentiment classes: Positive, Neutral, and Negative.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhen we map them:[m
[32m+[m[32m- LLM 'Polite' → 'Positive'[m
[32m+[m[32m- LLM 'Neutral' → 'Neutral'[m
[32m+[m[32m- LLM 'Angry' or 'Frustrated' → 'Negative'[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mSo if the LLM says 'Frustrated' and RoBERTa says 'Negative'—that's actually correct in our mapping![m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe 48% is conservative because it counts exact matches after mapping. What matters more is that we're using it as a second opinion—when both agree, we have high confidence. When they disagree, we flag for human review."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q8: Why train a model when you have a formula?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "That's an excellent question! We use the formula to CREATE the training labels—the 'correct answers' the model learns from.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mBut there are three reasons we train a model instead of just using the formula:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. **Missing data:** For a NEW complaint, we don't know the outcome yet. The formula needs breach_probability as input—but that's also a prediction! The GBM can predict priority WITHOUT knowing the outcome.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m2. **Learning real patterns:** The formula uses fixed weights (e.g., severity × 12). But maybe in OUR bank, severity matters MORE than we thought. The trained model can learn better weights from real data.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m3. **Smoothing:** When some features are missing (e.g., no amount listed), the formula would break. The model can interpolate intelligently.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe result is R² = 0.997—near-perfect reproduction of our formula, but more robust for real-world use."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q9: What features are most important for SLA breach?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "From our feature importance analysis, here are the top 10:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. **pct_sla_elapsed (10.2%)**: How far through the SLA window—most important![m
[32m+[m[32m2. **is_duplicate (9.9%)**: Duplicate complaints have different breach patterns[m
[32m+[m[32m3. **category_General (8.5%)**: General complaints have 30-day SLA[m
[32m+[m[32m4. **days_to_sla (7.8%)**: Base SLA window[m
[32m+[m[32m5. **sentiment_Polite (5.7%)**: Polite customers may get faster response[m
[32m+[m[32m6. **category_Loan (5.2%)**: Loan = 30-day SLA[m
[32m+[m[32m7. **severity_score (4.7%)**: Critical complaints get priority[m
[32m+[m[32m8. **sentiment_score (3.3%)**: Sentiment affects perceived urgency[m
[32m+[m[32m9. **account_type_loan (3.1%)**: Loan accounts handled differently[m
[32m+[m[32m10. **severity_Medium (2.1%)**: Medium is most common[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe key insight: the most important features are about TIME (pct_sla_elapsed) and the CATEGORY (which determines SLA window)."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q10: How do you handle class imbalance?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Class imbalance is when one class is much more common than another. In our case, only ~15% of complaints breach SLA—so if we trained a naive model, it could just predict 'no breach' for everything and get 85% accuracy![m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWe handle this in three ways:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. **SMOTE**: Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique. It creates synthetic examples of the minority class by interpolating between existing ones. Before: 150 breach / 850 no-breach. After SMOTE: ~680 / ~680.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m2. **class_weight='balanced'**: This tells the algorithm to pay more attention to the minority class during training. It's like giving extra points for getting the rare class right.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m3. **Stratified splitting**: When we split data into train/test, we maintain the same class ratio in both sets. Otherwise, the test set might have zero breaches by chance![m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mOur metrics show this works: 86% accuracy on a 15%-breach dataset, with proper precision and recall for both classes."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 5.3 System Integration Questions[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q11: How do ML models integrate with the LLM pipeline?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "We use a two-stage architecture:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Stage 1 (LLM Processing):**[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Intake Agent → Extracts structured fields[m
[32m+[m[32m2. Classifier Agent → Assigns category/severity/sentiment (LLM)[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Duplicate Detector → Finds similar complaints[m
[32m+[m[32m4. Response Drafter → Creates reply[m
[32m+[m[32m5. Root Cause → Clusters for systemic issues[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**Stage 2 (ML Verification):**[m
[32m+[m[32mAfter the LLM classifies, we run our ML models as second opinions:[m
[32m+[m[32m- ML Category (TF-IDF) → Verifies LLM category[m
[32m+[m[32m- ML Sentiment (RoBERTa) → Verifies LLM sentiment[m
[32m+[m[32m- SLA Monitor (XGBoost) → Predicts breach probability[m
[32m+[m[32m- Priority Scorer (GBM) → Scores urgency[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mBoth LLM and ML results are stored in the database and displayed on the dashboard. When they agree → high confidence. When they disagree → flag for human review.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe key point: ML models are SECOND opinions, not replacements. LLM remains primary, ML provides verification."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q12: What happens if an ML model makes a wrong prediction?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Three layers of protection:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. **Fallbacks:** Every ML agent has a rule-based fallback. If the SLA model can't load, we use a formula-based probability. The pipeline NEVER fails.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m2. **Second Opinion:** ML provides verification, not replacement. The dashboard shows BOTH LLM and ML results. Humans can see when they disagree.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m3. **Human-in-the-loop:** Users on the dashboard can click 'Correct' or 'Wrong' on any classification. This feedback:[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Goes to a feedback table[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Updates the display stats[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Could be used for future retraining[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m4. **Alert thresholds:** We don't treat all predictions equally. For critical complaints or high breach probability, we show alerts and banners regardless of ML confidence.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe goal is AI-augmented human decision-making, not fully automated replacement."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q13: How computationally expensive are these models?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Optimized for real-time use:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m| Model | Inference Time | Resource |[m
[32m+[m[32m|-------|---------------|----------|[m
[32m+[m[32m| Category (TF-IDF+LogReg) | <10ms | CPU |[m
[32m+[m[32m| Priority (GBM) | <5ms | CPU |[m
[32m+[m[32m| SLA (XGBoost) | <15ms | CPU |[m
[32m+[m[32m| Sentiment (RoBERTa) | ~200ms | CPU |[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mTotal additional latency: ~250ms per complaint[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mAll models run locally—no external API calls for ML (only for LLM via Groq). This means:[m
[32m+[m[32m- No API costs for ML[m
[32m+[m[32m- No network latency[m
[32m+[m[32m- Works offline if needed[m
[32m+[m[32m- Compliant with data residency requirements[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe models are serialized as joblib files (~10MB total) and ship with the repository."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 5.4 Advanced Questions[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q14: How would you retrain these models in production?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Simple commands for retraining:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```bash[m
[32m+[m[32m# Retrain SLA breach model with latest data[m
[32m+[m[32mpython -m models.train_sla_model[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m# Retrain category classifier[m
[32m+[m[32mpython -m models.train_category_classifier[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m# Retrain priority model[m
[32m+[m[32mpython -m models.train_priority_model[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn production, you'd:[m
[32m+[m[32m1. **Schedule:** Run weekly or monthly via cron[m
[32m+[m[32m2. **Trigger:** On-demand retraining when feedback shows degradation[m
[32m+[m[32m3. **Monitor:** Track accuracy over time, alert if it drops[m
[32m+[m[32m4. **Rollback:** Keep previous versions, easy to revert if needed[m
[32m+[m[32m5. **A/B test:** Deploy new model to subset of traffic first[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe models are stateless—retraining uses fresh data from the database and produces new joblib files. The dashboard automatically loads the latest model on restart."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q15: Can these models handle new categories or languages?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "For new categories: The current model supports 6 categories. Adding a 7th would require:[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Adding examples of the new category to training data[m
[32m+[m[32m2. Retraining the model[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Updating the category list[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mFor new languages:[m
[32m+[m[32m- **Intake & Classifier (LLM)**: Groq LLaMA handles English, Hindi, Marathi natively[m
[32m+[m[32m- **Category (TF-IDF)**: Works with any language—TF-IDF is language-agnostic[m
[32m+[m[32m- **Sentiment (RoBERTa)**: Pre-trained on multilingual tweets—works with Hindi/Marathi to some extent[m
[32m+[m[32m- **SLA (XGBoost)**: Language is a categorical feature—would need examples[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mFor Hindi/Marathi, the sentiment model might need fine-tuning or a language-specific model, but the TF-IDF category classifier would work with minimal changes."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q16: How do you explain model decisions to non-technical stakeholders?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "We use several approaches:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. **Feature Importance:** Show which features mattered most. For SLA: 'Percentage of SLA time elapsed' was #1—this is intuitive for business users.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m2. **Prediction Explanations:** For any single prediction, we can show:[m
[32m+[m[32m   - "This complaint is 82% likely to breach because:[m
[32m+[m[32m     - ✓ It's 90% through its SLA window[m
[32m+[m[32m     - ✓ Severity is Critical[m
[32m+[m[32m     - ✓ Customer has filed 3 previous complaints"[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m3. **Dashboard Visuals:** The Model Performance tab shows:[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Confusion matrices (read as: 'row = actual, column = predicted')[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Accuracy, precision, recall metrics[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Agreement rates between ML and LLM[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m4. **Business Metrics:** Translate to business terms:[m
[32m+[m[32m   - "94% AUC" → "We correctly identify high-risk complaints 94% of the time"[m
[32m+[m[32m   - "97% accuracy" → "Category classification is correct for 970 out of 1000 complaints"[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe goal is explainability through visualization and business translation, not technical detail."[m
[32m+[m
