[32m+[m[32m> We didn't just pick XGBoost arbitrarily. We ran a rigorous bake-off—testing 5 algorithms with 5-fold cross-validation. Here's what we found:[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> XGBoost (tuned) won with CV AUC of 0.916 and hold-out AUC of 0.94. In practical terms: when we show the model a complaint it's never seen, it predicts breach with 94% accuracy.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> The most important feature? Percentage of SLA time elapsed. Makes sense—the closer to the deadline, the higher the risk. Our team can now see exactly which complaints need immediate attention—before they become RBI violations."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Model 2: Category Classifier[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m> "Second, our Category Classifier. Every complaint needs to be routed to the right team.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> We use TF-IDF plus Logistic Regression. TF-IDF turns text into numbers while highlighting important words—like 'UPI' gets high weight, while 'the' gets zero. Logistic Regression then classifies using probability.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> Why not deep learning? For 6 categories with our data, this achieves 97% accuracy—better than neural networks would with limited data. And it's interpretable—we can show exactly which words caused the classification.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> Most importantly, it agrees with our LLM classifier 98% of the time. When they disagree, we flag for human review."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Model 3: Sentiment Model[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m> "Third, our Sentiment Model. Understanding customer emotion is crucial—an Angry customer needs different handling than a Polite one.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> We use a pre-trained RoBERTa transformer from HuggingFace—trained on 850 million tweets and fine-tuned for sentiment analysis. It runs locally on CPU, no API costs.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> The model outputs Positive, Neutral, or Negative. We map this to our 4-class system. Our agreement rate is 48%—sounds low, but it's because RoBERTa uses 3 classes while our LLM uses 4. When they disagree, we flag for human review. The key point: this is our second opinion, not replacement."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Model 4: Priority Scorer[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m> "Fourth, our Priority Scorer. Which complaint should we handle first?[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> We use Gradient Boosting to create a composite 0-100 score. The model was trained to mimic a human formula that combines severity, sentiment, amount, complaint history, age of complaint, and breach probability.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> The results: R-squared of 0.997—meaning it explains 99.7% of the variance in our priority formula. Mean absolute error of just 0.5 points. When we predict priority 75, the actual is almost always between 74 and 76.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> This gives our operations team a mathematically-grounded way to sort thousands of complaints by true urgency."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Model 5: Duplicate Detector[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m> "Fifth, our Duplicate Detector. Same customer, same issue, different channel.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> We use sentence-transformers—specifically all-MiniLM-L6-v2—to create 384-dimensional embeddings that capture SEMANTIC meaning. 'UPI not working' and 'UPI payment failed' have SIMILAR embeddings even though they're different words.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> These embeddings are stored in ChromaDB, a vector database. For each new complaint, we find the top-5 most similar complaints FROM THE SAME CUSTOMER. If similarity exceeds 0.78, we flag it as a duplicate.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> Why same customer only? Because DIFFERENT customers complaining about the same issue is a SYSTEMIC problem, not a duplicate. We handle systemic issues differently.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> This detected 86 duplicates—18.6% of our complaints were auto-resolved without drafting new responses."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Model 6: Root Cause Detection[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m> "Sixth, our Root Cause Detector. This finds SYSTEMIC ISSUES—clusters of similar complaints from multiple customers.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> We use KMeans clustering on the same embeddings from our Duplicate Detector—no re-embedding needed. We cluster all complaints into 12 groups.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> Then we analyze each cluster: Does it have at least 5 complaints? Is 60% or more from the same category? Where are these customers located?[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> Here's what we found: 6 systemic issues. For example—47 complaints about UPI failures concentrated in Nagpur. That's not 47 problems—that's ONE gateway failure that needs investigation.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> This is something no human can see looking at spreadsheets. But with KMeans on embeddings, the pattern emerges automatically."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Model 7: Customer Risk Score[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m> "Seventh, our Customer Risk Score. Not all customers are equal risk.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> We calculate three sub-scores: Ombudsman escalation risk (45% weight), Churn risk (30%), and Social media risk (25%).[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> Ombudsman risk considers breach probability, severity, amount, repeat complaints, and angry history. Churn risk looks at total complaints, unresolved count, and category breadth. Social risk checks Twitter/WhatsApp usage and angry sentiment.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> The composite 0-100 score helps identify high-risk customers for proactive management—before they escalate to RBI or leave the bank."[m
