[32m+[m[32m# Q&A Preparation - All Possible Questions[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## Fundamentals Questions[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q1: Explain machine learning to a non-technical person[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Imagine teaching a child to recognize cats. You show them many cat pictures—big cats, small cats, fluffy cats. The child learns patterns: whiskers, ears, tail. Now when they see a NEW cat they've never seen, they recognize it.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mMachine learning works the same way. We show computers thousands of examples with known answers. The computer learns patterns. Then when NEW data comes in—one it's never seen—it can make predictions.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn ComplaintIQ, our 7 models answer questions like: Will this breach its deadline? What category? Is the customer angry? How urgent? Is it a duplicate? What's the root cause? What's the customer's risk level?"[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q2: What's the difference between supervised and unsupervised learning?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Supervised learning is like learning with a teacher. We have the right answers—we know each complaint's category, severity, whether it breached. We show the model these examples, and it learns to predict.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mUnsupervised learning is learning without a teacher. We don't know the answers—we just have data, and the algorithm finds patterns on its own.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn ComplaintIQ:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Our 4 classification/prediction models use supervised learning—they're trained on labeled examples[m
[32m+[m[32m- Our Root Cause Detection uses unsupervised learning (KMeans clustering)—it finds groups of similar complaints without being told what to look for"[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q3: What is overfitting and how do you prevent it?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Overfitting is when a model memorizes training data instead of learning general patterns. It's like a student who memorizes past exam answers but fails on new questions.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWe prevent it in several ways:[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Train/test split: We keep 20% of data hidden, test on it[m
[32m+[m[32m2. Cross-validation: Train and test 5 times, average results[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Regularization: XGBoost adds penalties for complex trees[m
[32m+[m[32m4. SMOTE: Balances classes, prevents lazy predictions[m
[32m+[m[32m5. Early stopping: Stop when test performance stops improving[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mOur XGBoost has training accuracy 95% and test accuracy 94%—very close, so we're not overfitting."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q4: Explain AUC-ROC in simple terms[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "AUC-ROC measures how well a model distinguishes between two things—like separating 'will breach' from 'won't breach.'[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mImagine you're a detective. A perfect detective would have zero overlap—everybreach case is clearly marked 'high risk,' every non-breach is 'low risk.'[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe ROC curve plots this. The diagonal line is random guessing—50% accuracy. Our curve is much closer to the top-left corner.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mAUC is area under this curve—a single number from 0 to 1. Our model has AUC of 0.94. That means when we show the model two complaints—one that will breach, one that won't—it correctly identifies the higher-risk one 94% of the time."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q5: How do you handle class imbalance?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Class imbalance is when one class is much more common. Only ~15% of our complaints breach SLA—so a naive model could predict 'no breach' for everything and get 85% accuracy![m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWe handle it three ways:[m
[32m+[m[32m1. SMOTE: Creates synthetic minority examples—before: 150 breach / 850 no-breach; after: ~680 / ~680[m
[32m+[m[32m2. class_weight='balanced': Gives extra weight to minority class during training[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Stratified splitting: Maintains class ratio in train/test splits[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mOur metrics show this works: 86% accuracy on a 15%-breach dataset."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## Model-Specific Questions[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q6: How does XGBoost work?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "XGBoost builds an ensemble of decision trees, one after another. Each new tree corrects the previous ones' mistakes.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThink of it like a panel of experts:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Expert 1 gives opinion (40% breach probability)[m
[32m+[m[32m- Expert 2 corrects Expert 1's errors (+15%)[m
[32m+[m[32m- Expert 3 corrects Expert 2's errors (+10%)[m
[32m+[m[32m- ... 200 experts later ... final prediction 78%[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhat makes XGBoost special is regularization—it penalizes complex trees to prevent overfitting. Each 'tree' is questions like: Is pct_sla_elapsed > 0.8? Is severity Critical? Is sentiment Angry?"[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q7: How does TF-IDF work?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "TF-IDF stands for Term Frequency times Inverse Document Frequency. It converts text to numbers while highlighting important words.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mFormula: TF-IDF = (1 + log(TF)) × log(N/DF)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExample:[m
[32m+[m[32m- 'UPI' appears in 50 of 1000 complaints—so it's RARE, gets HIGH weight[m
[32m+[m[32m- 'the' appears in ALL 1000—so it's COMMON, gets ZERO weight[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhen we combine TF-IDF with Logistic Regression, we get a classifier that identifies categories based on important words. 'UPI' + 'payment' + 'failed' → high probability of UPI category."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q8: Why does sentiment model have only 48% agreement with LLM?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "This is a mapping issue, not a model failure.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mOur LLM uses 4 classes: Angry, Frustrated, Neutral, Polite[m
[32m+[m[32mRoBERTa uses 3 classes: Positive, Neutral, Negative[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhen we map:[m
[32m+[m[32m- LLM 'Polite' → 'Positive'[m
[32m+[m[32m- LLM 'Neutral' → 'Neutral'[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32m- LLM 'Angry' or 'Frustrated' → 'Negative'[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mSo if LLM says 'Frustrated' and RoBERTa says 'Negative'—that's actually correct in our mapping! The 48% is conservative because it counts exact matches.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWe use RoBERTa as second opinion—when both agree, high confidence; when they disagree, flag for review."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q9: Why train a model when you have a formula for priority?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Great question! We use the formula to CREATE training labels—the 'correct answers.'[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mBut we train a model because:[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Missing data: For NEW complaints, we don't know the outcome. The formula needs breach_probability—but that's ALSO a prediction![m
[32m+[m[32m2. Learning: The formula uses fixed weights. Maybe severity matters MORE than we thought. The model learns better weights from data.[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Smoothing: When features are missing, formula breaks. Model interpolates.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mR² = 0.997 means near-perfect reproduction but more robust for real-world use."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q10: How does the Duplicate Detector work?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "We use two components:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Sentence-Transformers (all-MiniLM-L6-v2): Creates 384-dimensional embeddings that capture semantic meaning—not keywords, but MEANING. 'UPI not working' and 'UPI payment failed' get SIMILAR embeddings.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m2. ChromaDB: Vector database that stores embeddings and enables fast similarity search.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mAlgorithm:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Index all complaints as embeddings in ChromaDB[m
[32m+[m[32m- For new complaint, embed it[m
[32m+[m[32m- Find top-5 similar from SAME CUSTOMER only[m
[32m+[m[32m- If similarity ≥ 0.78 → DUPLICATE[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhy same customer only? Different customers with same issue = SYSTEMIC, not duplicate."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q11: How does Root Cause Detection work?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "We use KMeans clustering on complaint embeddings:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Take all 384-dimensional embeddings from ChromaDB[m
[32m+[m[32m2. Run KMeans with k=12 (12 clusters)[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Each complaint assigned to nearest centroid[m
[32m+[m[32m4. For each cluster, check:[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Size ≥ 5 complaints?[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Category ≥ 60% dominant?[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Location analysis (top-3 cities)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExample output: '47 UPI complaints concentrated in Nagpur (80%)—possible local service issue'[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis catches patterns humans can't see—no human would notice 47 UPI complaints in Nagpur across thousands of rows."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q12: How do you calculate Customer Risk Score?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Three sub-scores:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. OMBUDSMAN (45%): Based on breach probability, severity, repeat complaints, amount, angry history[m
[32m+[m[32m   Formula: breach×40 + severity_pts + repeat_pts + amount_pts + angry_pts[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m2. CHURN (30%): Based on total complaints, unresolved count, category breadth[m
[32m+[m[32m   Formula: n_complaints×6 + unresolved×5 + categories×6[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m3. SOCIAL (25%): Based on Twitter/WhatsApp channel usage, angry sentiment[m
[32m+[m[32m   Formula: public_complaints×12 + channel_risk + angry_pts[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mFinal = 0.45×ombudsman + 0.30×churn + 0.25×social (all 0-100)"[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q13: What happens if an ML model makes a wrong prediction?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Three layers of protection:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Fallbacks: Every ML agent has rule-based fallback. If SLA model can't load, use formula-based probability. Pipeline NEVER fails.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m2. Second Opinion: ML provides verification, not replacement. Dashboard shows BOTH LLM and ML. Humans see when they disagree.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Human-in-the-loop: Users click 'Correct/Wrong' on dashboard. Feedback goes to database, updates stats, could be used for retraining.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mGoal is AI-augmented human decision-making, not full automation."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q14: How do you retrain models in production?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Simple commands:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```bash[m
[32m+[m[32mpython -m models.train_sla_model[m
[32m+[m[32mpython -m models.train_category_classifier[m
[32m+[m[32mpython -m models.train_priority_model[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn production:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Schedule weekly/monthly via cron[m
[32m+[m[32m- Trigger on-demand when feedback shows degradation[m
[32m+[m[32m- Track accuracy over time[m
[32m+[m[32m- Keep previous versions for rollback[m
[32m+[m[32m- A/B test new models on subset of traffic[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mModels are stateless—retrain uses fresh data from DB, produces new .joblib files."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q15: Can these models handle new categories or languages?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "For new categories:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Current: 6 categories[m
[32m+[m[32m- Adding 7th requires: new training examples + retrain + update list[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mFor new languages:[m
[32m+[m[32m- LLM (Intake/Classifier): Handles English/Hindi/Marathi natively[m
[32m+[m[32m- Category (TF-IDF): Language-agnostic, works as-is[m
[32m+[m[32m- Sentiment (RoBERTa): Pre-trained on multilingual tweets, may need fine-tuning[m
[32m+[m[32m- SLA (XGBoost): Language is categorical feature, would need examples[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mHindi/Marathi support is built into the LLM. TF-IDF handles any language. RoBERTa might need language-specific model for best sentiment results."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q16: What features are most important for SLA breach?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Top 10 from feature importance:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. pct_sla_elapsed (10.2%) — How far through SLA window[m
[32m+[m[32m2. is_duplicate (9.9%) — Duplicate complaints have different patterns[m
[32m+[m[32m3. category_General (8.5%) — General = 30-day SLA[m
[32m+[m[32m4. days_to_sla (7.8%) — Base SLA window[m
[32m+[m[32m5. sentiment_Polite (5.7%) — Polite customers may get faster response[m
[32m+[m[32m6. category_Loan (5.2%) — Loan = 30-day SLA[m
[32m+[m[32m7. severity_score (4.7%) — Critical = priority[m
