[32m+[m[32m9. account_type_loan (3.1%) — Loan accounts[m
[32m+[m[32m10. severity_Medium (2.1%) — Most common[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mKey insight: TIME (pct_sla_elapsed) and CATEGORY (determines SLA) matter most."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q17: Why use KMeans for root cause instead of rules?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Rules would require us to know what to look for:[m
[32m+[m[32m- 'If > 5 UPI complaints in same city in 7 days' → we'd need to write this rule[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mKMeans DISCOVERS patterns we don't know to look for:[m
[32m+[m[32m- It finds natural groupings in the embeddings[m
[32m+[m[32m- It can find unexpected clusters (maybe language-based? channel-based?)[m
[32m+[m[32m- It's unsupervised—we don't specify what to find[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExample: We found '47 UPI in Nagpur'—that's a specific pattern no human would think to write a rule for. The algorithm discovered it automatically."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q18: Why 0.78 threshold for duplicates?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "We tested different thresholds:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m- 0.90: Too strict → many duplicates missed[m
[32m+[m[32m- 0.85: Some duplicates missed[m[41m  [m
[32m+[m[32m- 0.78: Good balance → found 86 duplicates (18.6% auto-resolved)[m
[32m+[m[32m- 0.70: Too loose → false positives (different issues flagged as duplicates)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m0.78 was chosen by testing on labeled data—it's the point where precision and recall are balanced. We validated that flagged duplicates were actually duplicates."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q19: How do embeddings capture semantic meaning?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "The model (all-MiniLM-L6-v2) was trained on millions of sentence pairs:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m- "UPI not working" and "UPI payment failed" → similar embeddings[m
[32m+[m[32m- "Cat" and "Dog" → different embeddings[m
[32m+[m[32m- Trained using contrastive learning—similar sentences pulled together, different pushed apart[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe resulting embeddings capture CONTEXT and MEANING, not just keywords:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m- "UPI failed" → embedding A[m
[32m+[m[32m- "Transaction not working" → similar to embedding A (same meaning!)[m
[32m+[m[32m- "ATM broken" → different from embedding A (different category)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis is what enables semantic duplicate detection."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q20: How do you validate these models?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Rigorous validation:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. 5-fold Stratified Cross-Validation: Split into 5 parts, train on 4, test on 1, repeat 5 times, average[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m2. Hold-out test set: 20% of data never seen during training—we test on truly new data[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Multiple metrics: AUC, accuracy, precision, recall, F1—not just accuracy[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m4. Leaderboard: We test multiple algorithms, pick the winner based on CV AUC[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m5. Human feedback: Dashboard shows agreement rates, users can correct errors[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis isn't just 'we built it and it seems to work'—it's validated scientifically."[m
