[32m+[m[32m# PART 3: THE 7 ML MODELS - DETAILED EXPLANATION[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 3.1 Model 1: SLA Breach Predictor (XGBoost) (3-4 minutes)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m> "Let me start with what I consider our most important model - the SLA Breach Predictor.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **The Problem It Solves:**[m
[32m+[m[32m> Every bank knows their SLA windows - RBI mandates specific response times. But here's the challenge: with thousands of complaints, how do you know WHICH ones are at risk BEFORE they breach? By the time you notice, it's often too late.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **Our Solution: XGBoost**[m
[32m+[m[32m> We use XGBoost - Extreme Gradient Boosting - to predict the probability (0-100%) that any complaint will miss its RBI deadline.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **How It Works - The Simple Explanation:**[m
[32m+[m[32m> Think of XGBoost as a team of 200 experts, each asking a series of questions. Expert 1 asks: 'Is this complaint more than 80% through its SLA window?' If yes, that's already high probability. If no, Expert 2 asks: 'Is the severity Critical?' Expert 3 asks: 'Is the customer Angry?' Each expert gives a score, and we sum them all up to get a final probability.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **How It Works - The Technical Details:**[m
[32m+[m[32m> XGBoost builds an ensemble of decision trees. Each tree makes splits based on feature values. For example: 'IF pct_sla_elapsed > 0.8 AND severity_score >= 3 THEN high_breach_probability'.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> What makes XGBoost special is two things:[m
[32m+[m[32m> 1. Gradient Boosting - each new tree corrects the errors of all previous trees[m
[32m+[m[32m> 2. Regularization - it penalizes complex trees to prevent overfitting (memorizing training data instead of learning patterns)[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **The Features:**[m
[32m+[m[32m> We use 30+ features for each complaint:[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Time-based: hours_since_filed, pct_sla_elapsed, days_to_sla[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Severity: severity_score (Critical=4, High=3, Medium=2, Low=1)[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Sentiment: sentiment_score (Angry=4, Frustrated=3, Neutral=2, Polite=1)[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Customer: is_duplicate, is_repeat_customer, customer_complaint_count[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Channel: channel_risk (Twitter/WhatsApp = public = higher risk)[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Content: is_fraud_keyword, complaint_text_length[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **The Model Comparison - Our Bake-Off:**[m
[32m+[m[32m> We didn't just pick XGBoost arbitrarily. We tested 5 different algorithms:[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Random Forest[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Gradient Boosting[m
[32m+[m[32m> - LightGBM[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Stacking Ensemble (RF + XGBoost + LightGBM combined)[m
[32m+[m[32m> - XGBoost (with hyperparameter tuning)[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> We used 5-fold Stratified Cross-Validation with SMOTE to handle class imbalance (only ~15% of complaints breach). Here are the results:[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> | Model | CV AUC Score | Rank |[m
[32m+[m[32m> |-------|-------------|------|[m
[32m+[m[32m> | XGBoost (tuned) | 0.9157 | 1st |[m
[32m+[m[32m> | Gradient Boosting | 0.9095 | 2nd |[m
[32m+[m[32m> | Stacking | 0.9035 | 3rd |[m
[32m+[m[32m> | LightGBM | 0.9000 | 4th |[m
[32m+[m[32m> | Random Forest | 0.8952 | 5th |[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> XGBoost won! With a Cross-Validation AUC of 0.916 and a Hold-Out AUC of 0.94.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **What Does This Mean Practically?**[m
[32m+[m[32m> When we show the model a complaint it's NEVER seen before, it correctly identifies whether that complaint will breach its deadline 94% of the time.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **Feature Importance - What Matters Most:**[m
[32m+[m[32m> Our analysis shows:[m
[32m+[m[32m> 1. pct_sla_elapsed (10.2%) - How far through the SLA window - makes sense![m
[32m+[m[32m> 2. is_duplicate (9.9%) - Duplicate complaints have different patterns[m
[32m+[m[32m> 3. category_General (8.5%) - General category has 30-day SLA[m
[32m+[m[32m> 4. days_to_sla (7.8%) - The base SLA window[m
[32m+[m[32m> 5. sentiment_Polite (5.7%) - Polite customers may get faster responses[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> This gives us actionable insights - the model confirms that TIME and CATEGORY are the biggest predictors.[m
