[32m+[m[32m## 3.2 Model 2: Category Classifier (TF-IDF + Logistic Regression) (2-3 minutes)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m> "Now let's look at how we classify complaints into categories.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **The Problem It Solves:**[m
[32m+[m[32m> Every complaint needs to go to the right team. UPI complaints go to one team, Card to another, Loan to another. Wrong routing means delays. And different categories have different SLA windows.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **Our Solution: TF-IDF + Logistic Regression**[m
[32m+[m[32m> We use two classical ML techniques working together.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **Step 1: TF-IDF - Turning Text into Numbers**[m
[32m+[m[32m> TF-IDF stands for Term Frequency times Inverse Document Frequency. Let me explain what that means.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> Imagine you have this complaint text: 'UPI payment of Rs.5000 failed, money debited but not credited'[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> TF-IDF assigns weights to each word:[m
[32m+[m[32m> - 'UPI' appears in only 5% of all complaints, so it gets a HIGH weight (rare but important!)[m
[32m+[m[32m> - 'payment' appears in 30% of complaints, gets MEDIUM weight[m
[32m+[m[32m> - 'failed' appears in 20%, gets MEDIUM-HIGH weight[m
[32m+[m[32m> - 'the' appears in 100% (every complaint), gets ZERO weight (too common!)[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> The formula: TF-IDF = (1 + log(TF)) × log(N/DF)[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> We also use (1,2) n-grams - meaning it captures phrases like 'credit card' or 'net banking' as single features, not separate words.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **Step 2: Logistic Regression - The Classifier**[m
[32m+[m[32m> Once we have these TF-IDF weights, Logistic Regression acts like a weighted voting system.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> Each word has weights for each category:[m
[32m+[m[32m> - 'UPI' = +5.2 for UPI category, -3.1 for Card category[m
[32m+[m[32m> - 'ATM' = +4.8 for ATM category[m
[32m+[m[32m> - 'loan' = +4.5 for Loan category[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> When we input a complaint, it calculates scores for each category and uses softmax to convert to probabilities.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **Why This Approach?**[m
[32m+[m[32m> You might ask - why not use a neural network? For 6 categories with ~1000 training examples, TF-IDF + LogReg achieves 97% accuracy - better than deep learning would with limited data. Plus it's interpretable - we can show exactly which words caused the classification.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **Results:**[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Accuracy: 97%[m
[32m+[m[32m> - LLM Agreement: 98%[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Per-category performance: All categories 94-98% precision and recall[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **[Pause for questions]**[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m## 3.3 Model 3: Sentiment Model (RoBERTa) (2 minutes)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m> "Third - understanding customer sentiment.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **The Problem It Solves:**[m
[32m+[m[32m> An Angry customer needs different handling than a Polite one. Sentiment affects priority, risk scoring, and even whether we auto-resolve (Polite + Low/Medium severity = auto-resolve).[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **Our Solution: RoBERTa**[m
[32m+[m[32m> We use a pre-trained transformer model from HuggingFace - specifically cardiffnlp/twitter-roberta-base-sentiment-latest.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **What is RoBERTa?**[m
[32m+[m[32m> RoBERTa stands for Robustly Optimized BERT. It was trained on 850 million tweets and fine-tuned for sentiment analysis. That's huge - it learned from 850 million expressions of emotion![m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **How It Works:**[m
[32m+[m[32m> 1. Tokenization: The text is split into tokens (subwords)[m
[32m+[m[32m> 2. Embedding: Each token becomes a 768-dimensional vector[m
[32m+[m[32m> 3. Transformer Layers: 12 layers of self-attention analyze context[m
[32m+[m[32m> 4. Classification: Outputs probability for Positive, Neutral, Negative[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **The Class Mapping:**[m
[32m+[m[32m> Here's an important point - RoBERTa uses 3 classes, but our system uses 4. We map:[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Positive → Polite[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Neutral → Neutral[m
[32m+[m[32m> - Negative → Angry OR Frustrated[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **Why 48% Agreement with LLM?**[m
[32m+[m[32m> People sometimes ask - why is agreement only 48%? This sounds low but it's a mapping issue, not a model failure. When the LLM says 'Frustrated' and RoBERTa says 'Negative' - that's actually a MATCH after mapping. The 48% is conservative because it counts exact matches.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **Why Pre-trained Instead of Training From Scratch?**[m
[32m+[m[32m> Training from scratch would require 10,000+ labeled examples. Using pre-trained RoBERTa gives us enterprise-quality sentiment analysis without that data.[m
[32m+[m[32m>[m
[32m+[m[32m> **[Pause for questions]**[m
[32m+[m
