[32m+[m[32m## Fundamentals Questions[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q1: Explain machine learning to someone who doesn't know anything about it[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Let me use an analogy. Imagine you're teaching a child to recognize cats. You show them many pictures of cats - big cats, small cats, fluffy cats, skinny cats. The child learns patterns: whiskers, ears, tail. Now when they see a NEW cat they've never seen before, they can still recognize it.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mMachine learning works the same way. We show computers thousands of examples with known answers - in our case, complaints where we already know the category, severity, and whether they breached. The computer learns patterns in that data. Then when NEW data comes in - complaints the computer has never seen - it can make predictions.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn ComplaintIQ, our 7 models answer different questions: Will this breach its deadline? What category? Is the customer angry? How urgent? Is it a duplicate? What's the root cause? What's the customer's risk level?"[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q2: What is the difference between supervised and unsupervised learning?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Supervised learning is like learning with a teacher. We have the 'right answers' - for each complaint, we know the correct category, severity, whether it breached. We show the model all these examples, and it learns to predict.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mUnsupervised learning is like learning WITHOUT a teacher. We have data but don't know the answers. The algorithm finds patterns on its own.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn ComplaintIQ:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Our 4 classification/prediction models (SLA, Category, Sentiment, Priority) use SUPERVISED learning - they're trained on labeled examples[m
[32m+[m[32m- Our Root Cause Detection uses UNSUPERVISED learning (KMeans clustering) - it finds groups of similar complaints without being told what to look for"[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q3: What is overfitting and how do you prevent it?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Overfitting is when a model memorizes training data instead of learning general patterns. It's like a student who memorizes all answers to past exam questions but fails when given new questions.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWe prevent overfitting in several ways:[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Train/test split: We keep 20% of data hidden, test on it[m
[32m+[m[32m2. Cross-validation: We train and test 5 times with different splits, average results[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Regularization: XGBoost adds penalties for complex trees[m
[32m+[m[32m4. SMOTE: Balances classes to prevent lazy predictions[m
[32m+[m[32m5. Early stopping: Stop training when test performance stops improving[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mOur XGBoost has training accuracy 95% and test accuracy 94% - very close, which shows we're not overfitting - we're learning real patterns."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q4: Explain AUC-ROC in simple terms[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "AUC-ROC measures how well a model distinguishes between two things - like separating 'will breach' from 'won't breach'.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mImagine you're a detective trying to tell apart two groups. A perfect detective would have zero overlap - every breach case is clearly marked 'high risk', every non-breach is 'low risk'.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe ROC curve plots this. The diagonal line is random guessing - 50% accuracy. Our curve is much closer to the top-left corner.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mAUC is the area under this curve - a single number from 0 to 1. Our model has AUC of 0.94. That means when we show the model two complaints - one that will breach, one that won't - it correctly identifies the higher-risk one 94% of the time."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q5: How do you handle class imbalance?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Class imbalance is when one class is much more common than another. In our dataset, only about 15% of complaints breach SLA - the other 85% don't. If we trained a naive model, it could predict 'no breach' for everything and get 85% accuracy![m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWe handle it in three ways:[m
[32m+[m[32m1. SMOTE: Creates synthetic minority examples. Before: 150 breach / 850 no-breach. After SMOTE: about 680 / 680 - balanced.[m
[32m+[m[32m2. class_weight='balanced': This tells the algorithm to pay more attention to the minority class during training[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Stratified splitting: When we split data into train/test, we maintain the same class ratio in both sets[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mOur metrics show this works: 86% accuracy on a dataset where only 15% are breaches - that's real predictive power."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q6: How does XGBoost work? Explain like I'm 5.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Imagine you're asking a group of 200 experts for their opinion on whether a complaint will breach.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExpert 1 gives their opinion: 'I think there's a 40% chance of breach'[m
[32m+[m[32mExpert 2 looks at what Expert 1 got wrong and adds: 'Actually, add 15% more'[m
[32m+[m[32mExpert 3 looks at what Expert 2 missed and adds: 'Add another 10%'[m
[32m+[m[32m... and so on until Expert 200[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe final answer is the sum of all 200 experts' opinions, converted to a probability.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhat makes XGBoost special is that it doesn't just add up opinions - it regularizes. It penalizes experts who give overly complex opinions. This prevents the model from overfitting - memorizing the training data instead of learning real patterns."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q7: How does TF-IDF work?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "TF-IDF stands for Term Frequency times Inverse Document Frequency. It's a way to turn text into numbers while highlighting important words.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mLet me break it down:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Term Frequency (TF): How often does a word appear in THIS document?[m
[32m+[m[32m- Inverse Document Frequency (IDF): How RARE is this word across ALL documents?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExample from our data:[m
[32m+[m[32m- 'UPI' appears in only 50 out of 1000 complaints - it's RARE, so it gets a HIGH weight (important!)[m
[32m+[m[32m- 'the' appears in ALL 1000 complaints - it's COMMON, so it gets ZERO weight (not important!)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe formula: TF-IDF = (1 + log(TF)) × log(N/DF)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhen we combine this with Logistic Regression, we get a classifier that can identify categories based on important words. 'UPI' + 'payment' + 'failed' → high probability of UPI category."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q8: Why does the sentiment model only agree 48% with the LLM?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "This sounds like a problem, but it's actually a mapping issue, not a model failure.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mOur LLM classifier uses 4 classes: Angry, Frustrated, Neutral, Polite[m
[32m+[m[32mThe RoBERTa model uses 3 classes: Positive, Neutral, Negative[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWhen we map them:[m
[32m+[m[32m- LLM 'Polite' maps to RoBERTa 'Positive'[m
[32m+[m[32m- LLM 'Neutral' maps to RoBERTa 'Neutral'[m
[32m+[m[32m- LLM 'Angry' OR 'Frustrated' maps to RoBERTa 'Negative'[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mSo if the LLM says 'Frustrated' and RoBERTa says 'Negative' - that's actually CORRECT in our mapping![m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe 48% is conservative because it counts exact matches after mapping. What matters more is that we're using RoBERTa as a second opinion - when both agree, high confidence. When they disagree, we flag for human review."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q9: Why train a model when you already have a formula for priority?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Great question! We use the formula to CREATE the training labels - the 'correct answers' the model learns from.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mBut there are three reasons we train a model instead of just using the formula:[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Missing data: For a brand new complaint, we don't know the outcome. The formula needs breach_probability as input - but that's ALSO a prediction! The model can predict priority WITHOUT knowing the outcome.[m
[32m+[m[32m2. Learning real patterns: The formula uses FIXED weights (e.g., severity × 12). But maybe for OUR bank, severity matters MORE than we thought. The trained model can learn better weights from our actual data.[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Smoothing: When some features are missing (e.g., no amount listed), the formula would break. The model can interpolate intelligently.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe result is R² = 0.997 - near-perfect reproduction of our formula, but more robust for real-world use."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q10: How does the Duplicate Detector work?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "We use two components:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Sentence-Transformers (all-MiniLM-L6-v2): This creates 384-dimensional embeddings that capture SEMANTIC meaning - not just keywords, but the actual meaning of text. 'UPI not working' and 'UPI payment failed' have SIMILAR embeddings even though the words are different.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m2. ChromaDB: This is a vector database that stores embeddings and enables fast similarity search.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe algorithm:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Index: Every complaint gets embedded and stored in ChromaDB with metadata[m
[32m+[m[32m- Query: For a new complaint, we embed it[m
[32m+[m[32m- Search: We find the top-5 most similar complaints, BUT ONLY FROM THE SAME CUSTOMER[m
[32m+[m[32m- Compare: If cosine similarity ≥ 0.78 → DUPLICATE[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe 'same customer' part is critical - DIFFERENT customers with the same issue is a systemic problem (handled by Root Cause), not a duplicate."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q11: How does Root Cause Detection find systemic issues?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "We use KMeans clustering on the same embeddings from our Duplicate Detector.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mHere's how it works:[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Take all 384-dimensional embeddings[m
[32m+[m[32m2. Run KMeans with k=12 (12 clusters)[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Each complaint gets assigned to its nearest cluster center[m
[32m+[m[32m4. For each cluster, we check:[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Is it big enough? (≥5 complaints)[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Is one category dominant? (≥60% same category)[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Where are these customers located? (Top 3 cities)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExample output: The algorithm found 47 complaints about UPI failures that were 80% concentrated in Nagpur. That's not 47 problems - that's ONE gateway failure that needs investigation.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis is something no human could discover by looking at spreadsheets - but with KMeans on embeddings, the pattern emerges automatically."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q12: How do you calculate the Customer Risk Score?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "We calculate three sub-scores and combine them:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. OMBUDSMAN RISK (45% weight):[m
[32m+[m[32m   Formula: breach_probability×40 + severity_points + repeat_complaint_points + amount_points + angry_history_points[m
[32m+[m[41m   [m
[32m+[m[32m2. CHURN RISK (30% weight):[m
[32m+[m[32m   Formula: total_complaints×6 + unresolved×5 + category_breadth×6 + current_sentiment[m
[32m+[m[41m   [m
[32m+[m[32m3. SOCIAL MEDIA RISK (25% weight):[m
[32m+[m[32m   Formula: twitter_whatsapp_complaints×12 + current_channel_risk + angry_points + critical_points[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mFinal = 0.45×ombudsman + 0.30×churn + 0.25×social (all scaled to 0-100)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWe chose these weights because Ombudsman has highest business impact (RBI fines + reputation), Churn matters for customer retention, and Social matters for public visibility."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q13: What happens if an ML model makes a wrong prediction?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Three layers of protection:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. Fallbacks: Every ML agent has a rule-based fallback. If the SLA model can't load for some reason, we use a formula-based probability. The pipeline NEVER fails - always returns a result.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m2. Second Opinion: ML provides verification, not replacement. The dashboard shows BOTH LLM and ML results. When they agree → high confidence. When they disagree → we show a marker so humans can verify.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Human-in-the-loop: Users on the dashboard can click 'Correct' or 'Wrong' on any classification. This feedback goes to the database and updates stats. In future, this could be used for retraining.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe goal is AI-augmented human decision-making, not fully automated replacement."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q14: How do you retrain these models in production?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Simple commands:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m```bash[m
[32m+[m[32mpython -m models.train_sla_model[m
[32m+[m[32mpython -m models.train_category_classifier[m
[32m+[m[32mpython -m models.train_priority_model[m
[32m+[m[32m```[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mEach command retrains from the current database data and produces new .joblib model files.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mIn production, you'd:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Schedule: Run weekly or monthly via cron job[m
[32m+[m[32m- Trigger: On-demand retraining when feedback shows degradation[m
[32m+[m[32m- Monitor: Track accuracy over time, alert if it drops[m
[32m+[m[32m- Rollback: Keep previous versions, easy to revert if needed[m
[32m+[m[32m- A/B Test: Deploy new model to subset of traffic first[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe models are stateless - retraining uses fresh data from the database."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q15: Can these models handle new categories or new languages?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "For new categories:[m
[32m+[m[32m- Current system: 6 categories[m
[32m+[m[32m- Adding a 7th would require: new training examples with that category + retrain the model + update the category list[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mFor new languages:[m
[32m+[m[32m- LLM (Intake/Classifier): Already handles English, Hindi, and Marathi natively through Groq LLaMA[m
[32m+[m[32m- Category (TF-IDF): Language-agnostic - works with any language as-is[m
[32m+[m[32m- Sentiment (RoBERTa): Pre-trained on multilingual tweets - may need fine-tuning for best results on new languages[m
[32m+[m[32m- SLA (XGBoost): Language is a categorical feature - would need examples in new language[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe Hindi and Marathi support is built into the LLM. The TF-IDF category classifier handles any language. Only the sentiment model might need language-specific tuning."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q16: What features are most important for predicting SLA breach?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "From our feature importance analysis, the top 10:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. pct_sla_elapsed (10.2%) - How far through the SLA window - makes total sense![m
[32m+[m[32m2. is_duplicate (9.9%) - Duplicate complaints have different patterns[m
[32m+[m[32m3. category_General (8.5%) - General category has longest SLA (30 days)[m
[32m+[m[32m4. days_to_sla (7.8%) - The base SLA window[m
[32m+[m[32m5. sentiment_Polite (5.7%) - Polite customers may get faster responses[m
[32m+[m[32m6. category_Loan (5.2%) - Loan = 30-day SLA[m
[32m+[m[32m7. severity_score (4.7%) - Critical complaints get priority[m
[32m+[m[32m8. sentiment_score (3.3%) - Sentiment affects perceived urgency[m
[32m+[m[32m9. account_type_loan (3.1%) - Loan accounts handled differently[m
[32m+[m[32m10. severity_Medium (2.1%) - Most common severity level[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe key insight: TIME (pct_sla_elapsed) and CATEGORY (which determines SLA window) are the biggest predictors."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q17: Why use KMeans for root cause instead of writing rules?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "That's an excellent question! Rules would require us to know WHAT to look for:[m
[32m+[m[32m- 'If > 5 UPI complaints in same city in 7 days' - we'd need to write this rule[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mKMeans DISCOVERS patterns we don't know to look for:[m
[32m+[m[32m- It finds natural groupings in the embeddings[m
[32m+[m[32m- It can find UNEXPECTED clusters (maybe language-based? channel-based?)[m
[32m+[m[32m- It's unsupervised - we don't specify what to find[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mExample: We found '47 UPI complaints in Nagpur' - that's a specific pattern no human would think to write a rule for. The algorithm discovered it automatically from the data.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis is the power of unsupervised learning - it finds patterns humans can't see."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q18: Why 0.78 threshold for duplicates? How did you choose it?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "We tested different thresholds on our labeled data:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m- 0.90: Too strict → missed actual duplicates[m
[32m+[m[32m- 0.85: Some duplicates missed[m
[32m+[m[32m- 0.78: Good balance → found 86 duplicates (18.6% auto-resolved)[m
[32m+[m[32m- 0.70: Too loose → false positives (different issues flagged as duplicates)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m0.78 was chosen as the sweet spot where precision and recall are balanced. We validated that the flagged duplicates were actually duplicates by human review.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe threshold represents cosine similarity - 1.0 means identical, 0.0 means completely different. 0.78 means the complaints are semantically very similar."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q19: How do embeddings capture semantic meaning?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "The model (all-MiniLM-L6-v2) was trained on millions of sentence pairs using contrastive learning:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m- "UPI not working" and "UPI payment failed" → Similar embeddings (trained to be close)[m
[32m+[m[32m- "Cat" and "Dog" → Different embeddings (trained to be far)[m
[32m+[m[32m- "UPI failed" and "ATM broken" → Different embeddings (different meaning!)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe training objective was: minimize distance for similar sentences, maximize distance for different sentences.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThe resulting 384-dimensional embeddings capture CONTEXT and MEANING, not just keywords:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m- "UPI failed" → embedding A[m
[32m+[m[32m- "Transaction not working" → very similar to embedding A (same meaning!)[m
[32m+[m[32m- "ATM broken" → very different from embedding A (different category!)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis is what enables semantic duplicate detection - we find complaints that mean the same thing, even if they use different words."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q20: How do you validate these models? What's the process?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Rigorous scientific validation:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m1. **5-fold Stratified Cross-Validation:**[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Split data into 5 parts[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Train on 4 parts, test on 1[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Repeat 5 times with different splits[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Average the results[m
[32m+[m[32m   This ensures we're not just getting lucky with one split.[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m2. **Hold-out Test Set:**[m
[32m+[m[32m   - 20% of data is NEVER seen during training[m
[32m+[m[32m   - We test on truly unseen data[m
[32m+[m[32m   - This measures real-world performance[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m3. **Multiple Metrics:**[m
[32m+[m[32m   - We track AUC, accuracy, precision, recall, F1[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Not just accuracy (which can be misleading with imbalanced data)[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m4. **Algorithm Bake-off:**[m
[32m+[m[32m   - We test multiple algorithms (5 for SLA, several for each model)[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Pick the winner based on CV AUC[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Document the comparison[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m5. **Human Feedback:**[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Dashboard shows agreement rates[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Users can correct errors[m
[32m+[m[32m   - Tracks accuracy over time[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mThis isn't 'we built it and it seems to work' - it's validated scientifically."[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m---[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m### Q21: What's the computational cost? How fast are these models?[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m**A:** "Optimized for real-time use:[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32m| Model | Inference Time | Resource |[m
[32m+[m[32m|-------|---------------|----------|[m
[32m+[m[32m| Category (TF-IDF+LogReg) | <10ms | CPU |[m
[32m+[m[32m| Priority (GBM) | <5ms | CPU |[m
